Invoke `ebstopcode'
*******************

   Its usual way to invoke `ebstopcode' is as follows:

     % ebstopcode BOOK-PATH SUBBOOK

BOOK-PATH points to the top directory of a CD-ROM book where the file
`catalog' or `catalogs' resides.  It may be a remote access identifer
(`ebnet://...').  If BOOK-PATH is omitted, the current working
directory is assumed.

SUBBOOK is a directory name of the target subbook.  Use the `ebinfo'
command to see what subbooks your CD-ROM has:

     % ebinfo /cdrom
     disc type: EB/EBG/EBXA/EBXA-C/S-EBXA
     character code: JIS X 0208
     the number of subbooks: 2
     subbook 1:
       title: New English Japanese Dictionary (4th edition)
       directory: english
       search methods: word endword keyword menu
       font sizes: 16 24 30 48
       narrow font characters: 0xa121 -- 0xa24e
       wide font characters: 0xa321 -- 0xa27e
     subbook 2:
       title: CD-ROM French Japanese Dictionary (3rd edition)
       directory: french
       search methods: word endword keyword menu
       font sizes: 16 24 30 48
       narrow font characters:
       wide font characters: 0xa321 -- 0xa27e

(*Note Invoke `ebinfo': (ebinfo)Invoke ebinfo, for more details about
the `ebinfo' command).
In this example, there are two subbooks in the book, and their
directory names are `english' and `french'.

   Type the follwing to analyze text stop code of the `english' subbook:

     % ebstopcode /cdrom english

`ebstopcode' outputs text and candidates for stop code of the subbook,
like this:

     === stop-code?: 0x1f09 0x0001 ===
     
     === stop-code?: 0x1f41 0x0100 ===
     A
     
     === stop-code?: 0x1f09 0x0001 ===
     n 1: the blood group whose red cells carry the A antigen.
     
     === stop-code?: 0x1f09 0x0001 ===
     2: a metric unit of length equal to one ten billionth of a meter.
     
     === stop-code?: 0x1f09 0x0001 ===
     3: the basic unit of electric current adopted under the System
     International d'Unites.
     
     === stop-code?: 0x1f09 0x0001 ===
     
     === stop-code?: 0x1f41 0x0100 ===
     (snip)

   Each `stop-code?:' line shows a candidate for stop code.  Specifying
it as text stop code, EB Library stops displaying text at the point.

   The appropriate stop code of the `english' subbook is "0x1f41
0x0100".  Test the stop code using `--no-candidate' and `--code'
options:

     % ebstopcode --no-candidate --code "0x1f41 0x0100" /cdrom english
     A
     n 1: the blood group whose red cells carry the A antigen.
     2: a metric unit of length equal to one ten billionth of a meter.
     3: the basic unit of electric current adopted under the System
     International d'Unites.


